summary.seg: This manuscript, probably produced during the 12th century, is a Menologion for November, a liturgical book containing the hagiographical texts to be read in church during that month, including Lives of Saints, martyrdom narratives and accounts regarding relics and posthumous miracles.

All but one of the saints' Lives found in this volume are the work of Symeon Metaphrastes, or Symeon the Metaphrast, a 10th-century Byzantine civil official and later a monk. He rewrote numerous existing hagiographical texts in a more accessible style and compiled these into a new menologion. The term Metaphrast refers to this practice of rewriting. Symeon's versions of these stories became the most widely used, superseding those read previously. It also contains two homilies forming part of the hagiographical cycle, respectively the work of the great patristic theologian and Patriarch of Constantinople John Chrysostom (c. 344-407) and the Byzantine poet, hymnographer and Metropolitan of Euchaita Ioannes Mauropous (d. c. 1092).
Three replacement folios were added to replace original ones which had been lost, probably in the later 12th or 13th century (ff. 1 and 195-196).

During the early modern period the manuscript was owned by the Monastery of the Pantokrator on Mount Athos, as indicated by a note on f. i verso, dated 1517/8. It was bought from the Pantokrator, along with many other manuscripts, by the classicist Richard Bentley (1662-1742), Master of Trinity College. What may be another ownership note, on f. ii verso, has been partially erased, eliminating the words actually identifying the owner. This could have been done deliberately, to protect a later owner's claim on the manuscript, a common occurrence.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [a] + i-ii + 1-197 + [b], in brown ink, in Arabic and Roman numerals, recto, upper right.

additions.p: There is a note of ownership of the Monastery of the Pantakrator on Mount Athos, dated 1517/8, on f. i verso: Βιβλίον τοὺ Παντοκράτορος Χριστοῦ τὴν ἐν τῶ ἁγἰω ὄρει ἔτους ͵ζκϛʹ ἰνδικτιῶνος ϛʹ.
There is a largely illegible note in Greek onf. i recto and some scribbles and pen-trials.

binding.p: 18th-century full leather binding over couched-laminate boards, with plain pastedowns. There is decorative blind tooling on the edges of the boards and gold tooling on the spine. The title Vitae Sanctorum MS is tooled in gold on a red label on the spine, and the classmark appears on patches.
binding.condition: Both outer joints are partially split. Both endcaps are damaged and the tailband is partially detached.

accMat.p: There is a single paper endleaf at each end, belonging to the current binding, ff. [a] and [b], within which at the left-hand end is a parchment endleaf f. i). This was in place by 1518, when a dated note was added to f. i verso, but probably does not date to the original production of the manuscript, as this leaf does not bear pest damage corresponding to that of the following original endleaf f. ii, which bears the contents list.
Inserted loose between ff. 165 and 166 is a small fragment of Western paper containing part of a note in vernacular Greek addressed to the skeuophylax Avakoum.

provenance.p: Owned by the Monastery of the Pantokrator Monē Pantokratoros (Athos, Greece) on Mount Athos in 1517/8.
Purchased from the Abbot of the Pantokrator by Richard Bentley (1662-1742) Bentley, Richard, 1662-1742 , Master of Trinity.

history.acquisition: Bequeathed to Trinity College by Bentley.

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), quite thick and of poor quality, with a marked contrast between the colour of flesh-side and hair-side and a considerable number of holes dating to the time of production, sometimes within the written area (e.g. ff. 107, 185).

collation.p: This part consists of 25 quires, of which one is a binion and the rest are quaternia.

list.item: Quire 18-1+1 ff. 1-8 The original first folio has become detached (it is now f. 197) and later replaced by another (f. 1).
Quires 2-248 ff. 9-192 Quire 13 (ff. 97-104) is bound upside-down.

Quire 254-2+3 ff. 193-197
The original second and third folios have been lost, and later replaced by others; the detached original first folio of Quire 1 has been bound in here as the last folio.

collation.signatures: There are quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in pencil, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right. They survive on all quires (1-25).

supportDesc.condition: ff. 33, 105 and 112 have been detached and reattached to stubs with stitching, while f. 73 has also been detached and reattached to a stub, probably by pasting. A strip of parchment has been wrapped around ff. 97-104, perhaps to repair damage. There are losses to the head-edge of ff. 3-25, causing slight loss of text to some folios. The outer margins of ff. 26 and 125 have been cut away, as has the lower outer corner of f. 94. There are occasional small tears to the edges of folios and small holes elsewhere. There is pest damage to the outermost folios. There is significant cockling, creasing, drops of wax, water staining and areas of dirt. The ink is occasionally abraded, notably in the case of the headpiece and heading on f. 68v, and abraded text has sometimes been overwritten (e.g. f. 3r).

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. 2r-194v and 197r-197v Two columns of 33 lines each.
214 170
Pricking sometimes survives in the lower and upper margins, but much has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type 30C2. Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: ff. ii rect-ii verso, 2r-194v and 197r-197v were copied by Hand A in an upright mixed minuscule script, in brown ink, with modest variation in letter size. Tails are sometimes flourished into the lower margin, especially that of the abbreviation of καί, and are sometimes looped (e.g. ff. 134v-135v).

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear only at the end of lines. Breathings are both angular and round, and mute iota is absent. Use of the double dot is functional only. Nomina sacra are abbreviated only when more than two letters long or with enclitics. Circumflexes appear above breathings, but are not enlarged when they do so. The double grave accent is in use.
When the abbreviation of καί appears in the bottom line, it tends to take the form of a single diagonal stroke continuing into a long flourished tail below (e.g. ff. 123v-125v.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop.
Headings are written in Alexandrine majuscule script with some minuscule forms, in red ink.

decoDesc.decoNote: The beginning of each text is preceded by a small rectangular headpiece in red ink.
The beginnings of sections are marked by simple minor initials in red ink.
The beginning of the contents list on f. ii recto is preceded by a simple vignette in brown and red ink.
Before some texts space has been left for the headpiece but this has never been added, e.g. ff. 42v, 79r.

additions.p: There is an note in Greek on f. ii verso, possibly recording ownership which is much abraded, perhaps due to deliberate erasure. Another note near the foot of f. ii verso has been almost entirely erased. There are other occasional brief annotations in Greek by various hands.
A later hand, possibly Hand B, has erased and replaced some text on f. ii recto. Another hand has erased and replaced text on f. 50r.

history.origin: The characteristics of the script suggest that the main body of the manuscript was copied in the 12th century.

support.material: Parchment, of medium thickness and quality.

collation.p: This part consists of three replacement folios, ff. 1 and 195-196.

supportDesc.condition: There is slight pest damage, significant cockling and creasing, drops of wax, water staining and extensive areas of dirt.

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. 1r-1v and 195r-196v Two columns of 34 lines. 210 160
Pricking survives in all three margins, but some has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, type 00C2. Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: ff. 1r-1v and 195r-196vwere copied by Hand B in mixed minuscule script, slanting slightly to the right, in brown ink, with moderate variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all lengths of nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to letters and abbreviations. Circumflexes appear enlarged above breathings.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower comma, question mark and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: The beginnings of sections are marked by simple minor initials is red ink. The text on f. 1r begins with a larger, more ornate initial in red ink.

physDesc.additions: The scribe has added marginal ση(μείωσαι) marks highlighting significant passages.

history.origin: These folios were inserted to replace lost original folios, probably in the second half of the 12th or 13th century, as suggested by the style of script.
